Growing in up Los Angeles, it didn’t take me very long to realize I wasn’t mean enough to be rich. I saw firsthand the dreadful effect of exposure. I can see a sharksfin from 20 miles away. And I can smell blood before the wound takes shape. I’ve won, but more importantly I’ve learned what a real loss is. My definition of tough has nothing to do with fighting. I don’t think anyone’s life is more or less important than mine. But mine is mine & I paint my life. I crawl through the experience and use it for fuel. My experience. My time. All books inspire me. “I have not collected art. Art collected me. I never found paintings. They found me. I have never even owned a work of art. They owned me.”
#edwardgrobinson

If I had a dollar for every time someone called me an Art fag my 37 Chevy would have been painted a long time ago. Especially in my “working” career. Things as a whole are a little better but it wasn’t always cool to tattoo your body & roll around on chopped up shit. To make Art.  Individuality was and is seen as a threat. Every single one of these paintings every word I write pushes back against this. Bullies. Squares. The two tons of grease in your hair the gold teeth the way you dress should make you feel on top of a mountain. Despite what they say, being a weirdo is a good thing. My people. Anybody who puts their shit out there for the world to judge knows the crippling anxiety that accompanies it. Friggin mean ass people everywhere. BUT there are also those who get it. Who want to exchange ideas, who’re just as terrified as you that someone is gonna laugh, say something smart. Fuck em. Pick up the brush, the welder, the guitar, the pencil, the scissors, anything, and create. Produce. Make it your life’s mission to leave a document of how YOU feel about being in the world. You never know, you could inspire someone. It’s been worth it for me, despite all the doubt & “what’s up Bay Area, art guy” comments. I am connected to all those who came before me letting their freak and geek flag fly. 
I always feel I write too much and who the hell is gonna read this but oh well. I already jumped long ago. No safety net. 
Your brother in arms, 
Jake.

Somebody DM’d me saying I was a horrible salesman & it made me feel … wonderful. Simplicity is my ultimate goal. Harmlessness. Gratitude & LOVE. I love painting. I love my wife. I love my friends. I paint my life. There are no complications, no go backs, no second guessing ,,, go for it then take it down tack up a new one & repeat. I am hooked like a research monkey. The more I figure out the less I feel I know & the more I study. Study study & let it come forth organically in joy & wonderment. If there is a secret to allow the muse to break the threshold of my studio I will never tell. There are certain aspects of the mystery that critics & skeptics can comment on or try to investigate — but this is not the job of the Artist. The job of the Artist is to show a true heart to the world. Our anxieties and fears & expectations — our wild dreams are our common thread. The shattering is where the sun can seep in … and keep the negative naysayers … away. You gotta be smarter than 
They are

Evil.

Your friend!

Lately I’ve been feeling like my guts & chest are hooked up to an electrical barbwire fence. Sober as a god damn judge, no cigarettes, just the light in the back of my brain swinging around. Maybe 3 hours sleep. I read a lot of Artist biographies, & Artist statements at shows. All very intellectual & concise. I paint to deal with my eternal loneliness. I grew up with a lot of tough people, lotsa tough love. Painful serious lessons. In my life I’m grateful I never fronted. I’m not from the hood. I don’t claim to be any kinda gangster. I’ve always had to deal head on with this gnawing sensitivity. This is why I paint & this is what I did today after yoga to confront it. As I write this there’s a funnybone tingle from my belt buckle to the tips of my hair & I paint to deal with this. I write poems to deal with this. Most days I’m good but when I’m not I repeat over & over that it’ll pass and I’ll be cruisin again out by the coast in my 37 or maybe one day I’ll figure out how to get the Panhead running right. I’m grateful for all these outlets. The only way I can see to get through. The booze & the drugs and the cigs are a friggin scam. Best to bend right into it; eye to eye. Thank you for all the nice messages & the comments. I appreciate it. 
Onward & upward. 
Your friend 
Coulter Jacobs.

battleships yearning
to return 
Like a butcher
walking all over my heart
with imitated footsteps,
Slandering, polluting,
Dirty as a suntan 
Smudged passion ignoring 
the brilliant diminishing 
memories.

I think alot about style & I don’t know why. I’ve had the discussion with friends as to why it’s important & why it’s not. I guess if it matters to you it really does; and if it doesn’t, it doesn’t. I don’t think much about algorithms & computers or about branding or marketing or anything in this realm … although the other day I did learn how to turn a document into a PDF. I can’t say enough how grateful I am that Artists I admire come to visit me & we discuss ideas & we discuss how to survive in the world that changes drastically second by second. I especially appreciate the feedback & company of younger Artists. I go see the old guys, too. I meet people organically & I bow my head every night & say thank you for friendship & for the Arts. I hold individuality in the highest regard & as I get older I realize I’m surrounded by people who are unabashedly THEMSELVES. Photographers, guitar players & drummers, Kustom car builders, painters, poets, tattooers, motorcycle mechanics & ceramicists, chefs & comedians … all searching for and embracing STYLE. How it is to be you in a world that’s always been insane. It’s a truly beautiful thing if you let it be. Keep your eyes on the prize. 
With all my Love & all my respect to all the Rebels out there, showing their spirit & their GUTS! It’s the only thing. 
Your friend. 
Jake.

All you can ask for is a little honesty. As time goes on, if you’re lucky, you can become honest with yourself. You can accept yourself. There is no door A if you walked through door B. Some circumstances you just can’t change. But you can be honest. Not a liar a cheat or a thief. Learn how to recognize & accept a defeat & stand firm in the face of bad luck. If you can, put the vices down & check in with your real heart. I guess it’s kind of silly writing all this on an app, but I do what I can to keep up technologically. I get shit from people but I choose to focus on the positive part of it; the communication part. I’ve made some real friends participating in this platform. And for that I’m grateful. I’m grateful I’ve gotten as far as I have in this crazy world, and I’m so glad there’s still the opportunity to slow down & read & paint & drive slow around the peninsula & putt the bike along staring out at the ocean. My computer died months ago and it doesn’t even matter.  The Art Supply is open & a few people who I hold dear still take my calls … thank you all who send me nice messages & all the visitors to my studio. It really means a lot to me. Happy humpday!

The poetry thing has never been a good talking point in the circles I run in. 
An old school tatt guy I knew told me the answer to every poem is to suicide or not to suicide. Either do it or get the fuck on. Stop complaining. I graduated San Diego State with a degree in journalism & couldn’t even get a job as a god damn janitor at the Union Tribune. (I applied for an entry level janitor position, twice.) My writing was & continues to be widely turned down. If I’m totally honest there’s part of me, a large part, that likes this. To not be accepted; to not be “cool.” Everything is cool now. It didn’t used to be. Even in my lifetime cops & firefighters & athletes used to look down on tattoos. I was drawn to the unacceptable. The different. The individual. Tell somebody on a construction site you’re working on a new book of poetry or a new painting & let me know how it goes. I love this. Going on a social media app in my 40’s talking about yoga & bunnies & typing my poems out. I hear the snide comments & I wanna tell you all, I appreciate it so much. What else shall we discuss here —the biography of Samuel Steward? My new yoga shorts? The bonding process of Holland Lops? Transcendental Meditation? Haaaaa ,,, as my man Bob said:

Always on the outside of whatever side there was 
When they asked him why it had to be that way, well, he answered, just because

It never gets easier. The paintings, the poems, the push ups & the tinkering with the cars & bikes … the navigating personalities in my work & personal life. The more I read and the more I meditate & the more I investigate my heart it never gets easier. The questions & the head shake & drop; the bewilderment is ongoing. The more I consciously work toward harmlessness the more I’m tested against harmful people. It’s gotten to the point of laughter for me; I accept it. And I can just close my mouth & walk to my studio & listen to Miles Davis & smile away for hours on end as the cars crash and the banks are looted & somebody you thought was a friend aims a knife for your spinal column. The few real friends I do have check in & say I Love You brother before we hang up the phone. My love for my wife grows deeper by the second right along side my Love for the Arts & the individual seeking a true voice & stance. A stance for truth & beauty & peace & for quiet. This is a lifestyle that I was lucky enough to be introduced to & it’s proven worthy in every Artist biography I read. It’s the sacred ridiculousness that makes zero sense & at the same time can save your mother fucking life if you let it.

I promise you I’m not going to be one of those dudes talking about how there was no internet in “my day” ,,, things were so much better before or after this blah blah … I can’t even fully express how corny I think this is. Nobody is forcing anyone to use the internet or to participate in anything technologically. You can learn to hunt & gather & live in the woods at anytime & watch how quickly you’re forgotten. I think self righteousness is one of the worst things humans can fall in to. What I’M saying is “my day” is right this second & I’m actively trying & working to bend & have my opinion changed and updated under the still basic teachings of no lying no stealing no cheating & no snitching. Other than that bring it on & I can do my duty as a human to find something good in any situation. To connect, somehow. Lately I go into the studio with absolutely no plan just start moving it around, work on my self talk & try my best to let the childlike part of my brain get a little sunlight. Don’t ever forget: RIGHT NOW is your time; you can dress up like the 60’s & you can wax philosophical about how rad everything was in the 80’s & waste your breath away on nostalgia & miss the here and now … or you can keep it fresh right in the center of your mind that everyone has anxiety everyone struggles with something everyone can get low down & you can just be nice. Especially when someone isn’t nice to you. “Back in the day” I wish I would have understood this deeper & could implement it. Today, I can. 
Your long winded Friend, 
Jake

Man I am so lucky & so grateful I found this Artist life. It never stops challenging me — working the drawings & pushing the surfaces; experimenting with materials. It’s unending. Hours & hours go by in minutes & I got the tunes going, books open & I’m MOVING, getting surprised & baffled & turning corners … I don’t post everything I make & I don’t want to front like all the galleries are beating down my door or front like the paintings are sold before the paint is dry. I am still a lowly civil servant when it comes down to it; creeping up on 20 years of City service. My work in fiction, poetry & painting has been mostly ignored by the establishment. Sometimes it gets me down other times I’m stoked on it & increasingly I just don’t care. And I’m not on Front Street when I say I bought a 37 Chevy a 59 panhead & my own shop to tinker around on it all through selling Art. I am very proud of this. Small working class victories. The accolades may elude me but I have a loyal and sometimes repeat “client” base who visit & stay in touch & purchase the work. “Outsider Art” “Folk Art” “Low Art” all these labels I am not uncomfortable with. I even donated some original paintings to a thrift store down the street & I think often of Thom DeVita showing works at his local craft fair & being proud of the ribbons. I’ve gone to a few openings lately & its great to be an unknown & just watch the scene from a quiet corner. Every once in awhile I meet people organically who become friends …
Happy Monday to all! Another week ahead to check things off the list. 
Your brother in arms,
Jake.

I’m the type of dude who rewinds the song before it’s over … again & again & again. And I believe in the fake jog … crossing an intersection with a car waiting I always wave & do the fake jog … some people make 5 paintings & have a show at Gagosian; others are “discovered” in their 70’s & 80’s … some are never known at all … there is no formula, no path, no concrete examples … I get asked tons of questions relating to this & I have zero answers. I don’t label art. I don’t really schmooze … I see graffiti I love & I can go to the Norton Simon and stare at the Rembrandts for hours. Ric Clayton’s work is just as important to me as Arshile Gorky’s. 
I just combine things I like:
Film, art history, kustom cars, lowriders, old Harley’s, furniture, tile & lighting, old buildings, porcelain signs— it goes on & on …
I like seeing the work in beautiful spaces; if people approach me I evaluate the situation & make a decision. (I’m averaging a show every 5 years 😂.) 
Every single artist I know dreams of finding someone on the gallery/management side who cares about the work as much as he/she does & takes care of that side of it. 
I have not found that yet, but I am hopeful …
Petting a dog in the art supply the other day, the owner turned around, 
“How did you do that? She never lets Anyone pet her??”
I laughed, “It’s because I do the fake jog.”
She just kinda looked at me, blank, & I walked out to Hollywood Blvd. 
Still laughing to myself … 
Thank you Thank you to all who message me & leave nice comments. I’m more in Love with painting than ever. Dead ass sober 8 months, today. 
Your friend,
Jake.

This one is for Jean-Louis Lebris de Kérouac … who I found when I was 19 years old & changed the direction of my life. Just like most of the greats he was savaged in the press … “this isn’t writing it’s typewriting” etc. etc. … John Fante & even F. Scott Fitzgerald died outta print & everyone knows what they did to Van Gogh & they did it to Guston & they did it to Bob Dylan too … the lesson always the same: do it for yourself; to friggin save yourself. If you need it you know it & if you’re doing it to appease others everyone can see that too. There are plenty of people out there ready to jump in front of the cameras and represent. 9 times outta 10 the real version of this representation is in a quiet place somewhere, working. These days people are mostly just good at google & strive to look like they have credentials they didn’t earn. My wife told me about a website Substack where I feel like I can expand the writing & post old photos, poems & essays. Talk some shit. Rant. Plenty to be grateful for in this world & there are still things I think are totally valid to be angry about. I just try to pay homage to, and stay close to the source of things I love. The history. Roots. Beginnings. And I don’t claim ever. My way might not be the right way, but it’s the only way you’ll get from me. I haven’t figured out how to use the website yet, but I’m gonna learn. Enough with all this, now. 
Your long winded brother in arms,
Jake. 
As always, thank you for “following me” (I hate it’s called that) … and thanks for all the nice messages. 
Cheers to Friday night! ——poor folks time to SHINE!

You have to be careful 
When painting 
that you don’t 
Learn how to paint 

Impulse 
No rules 
Total freedom 
Every artist who makes a great work of art 
Enriches the work of every other contemporary artist
There is no competition 
No time no boss no consequences 
Do the opposite of what the experts say
Fling & flail & weep & above all else blast the music
Art is done in secret 
Show it or don’t
Go too far and whimper 
Keep your head up
Fend off the hangers-on
Those who do not produce
The person with a fancy title 
Daddy’s boy rich kids are the worst to kick it with 

Contemplate beautiful things
The ugliest scum at the back of the oven 
Explore & disturb the universe 
And know please know 
What a wise man said:

Most of the evil in this world is done by people with 
Good intentions. 
Everyone thinks they’re “right” …
There is no right or wrong
Only up & down

GO UP. 
See you there. 

“Bloodshot Consequences”
72 x 72 inches. 
All the way ((LIVE)) in the LA HARBOR. 
Your friend,
Coulter Jacobs.

I been sick as shit all week (covid negative) sore throat no energy & my shoulder hurts so bad I feel like I could vomit & I’m moping around, find a huge canvas under my work bench & all I could concentrate on doing to get the paint moving is start cleaning out the tubes squirting the shit on the canvas for no reason I have a god damn migraine & there are razor blades in my shoulder & I’m outta my friggin mind I’m either a possessed genius or the stupidest mother fucker in a 3000 mile radius I start to see the damn thing take shape can’t sleep thinking about it limp to the art supply stay up til 2 o’clock in the morning pushing the paint around gasping for breath sore, haven’t eaten anything all day except an apple & two cups of coffee wake up out here in my boxers with paint between my toes & I’m seeing it appear take a shower finally 4 o’clock put my painting clothes on … in it again too many ideas try to real it in tossing tube after tube in the trash & I step back & think: what the hell is wrong with me why am I doing this I am a ridiculous possessed idiot but I laugh it off & go inside to pet the bunny & watch a documentary about Portland Noir exhausted snapped outta this trance & I laugh & laugh & laugh & I think I’ll go for a bike ride.

I was so wrong. 

When the internet first came along I was sure it would be the end of all wars. I thought, so foolishly, people could finally communicate, and come together. Driving around this city it’s just a shame what is happening. The trash the poverty the needles in the gutter, somebody’s child filthy, living on Sunset Blvd. Vacant signs everywhere; the whole thing becoming so commonplace. Step over a person who could be dead or alive. It breaks my friggin heart. People will slit your throat & not think twice in pursuit of money. No shame. The gap between right & wrong becoming wider. The guy at the top wants it ALL. Most days I wish I was born in some small fishing village & I didn’t know about any of this. I’m getting closer & closer to bringing this into reality. My family has been in Los Angeles for 4 generations & I don’t recognize most of it anymore, at all. Bring on the bulldozers and wrecking balls. The show is just getting started as the writers picket & the politicians sell contracts the needles are plunged into veins the gas is 6 dollars a gallon & it’s all so incredibly sad. I’m so sad sitting in here painting pictures acting like none of this is happening. Time to twist the throttle of the Pan around the peninsula & follow the headlight, hoping for a 5th 6th & 7th gear.

97,000 miles

THANK YOU!

The one side 
Exalts 
The con man 
The other side
The con artist 
Red & Blue
And I lasso the
Muse
Clamor & chatter 
Little progress
5 bucks is 5 cents 
As the phone booths
Disappear
And I wrestle the
Muse
A terrible envelope 
Sophisticated war movies
Hamlet, Laurence Olivier, 
22 years old on Broadway &
5th 
Hooked to the gills 
And I chase the
Muse
Pinpoint pupils, top ranked
Welterweight, glides by
In a sea green Cadillac 
Dreaming Bogart, Cagney, Edward G. Robinson 
Through the bombed out ruins
I genuflect before the
Muse
The marrow, sea floor deep resentment 
Of authority
As a child & into my teenage years, I heard over
And over
“The only place you’ll find fair, is in the dictionary”
And I lay awake
Listening to Billie Holiday
In the squid ink darkness 
Praying for the
Muse
Impulsive & explosive 
The liar given awards
The snitch promoted 
Rubber boots descend
The ship ladder
And I burst sweat
For the
Muse
And I paint these pictures
And write these lines
And I know how mean people can be
But I know the reward of 
Kindness, and I know humility 
And I know it shouldn’t 
Matter
But it does. 

“Lassoing the Muse”
72 x 72”

(Three self portraits in a week)
All the Way Live in the Los Angeles Harbor
Happy Monday!
Your old pal,
Coulter Jacobs.

It’s a tricky thing meeting your heroes. I’m not a super outgoing person & I don’t get out much … I’ve been both inspired & disappointed when face to face with somebody I admire. When I met Chad Koeplinger I was charged with inspiration. It felt like I’d known him for 20 years. His energy was immaculate, calm & urgent at the same time. I don’t usually take commissions, but for him I would run through a brick wall & this painting is for a buddy of his who asked Chad about purchasing work from me. I immediately said yes. Nervous as fuck I got to work on a study & sweated through the painting. I even consulted his homie about color & specifics. In the end it was a challenge I’m glad I accepted. I’m getting better at introducing myself and letting people know I am inspired by their work — with no expectations. You never know, you could end up calling one of your heroes a friend. That’s what it’s all about. Hope everyone is having a productive Monday. And to the too cool self important pricks out there: you will get what you deserve in the end. The shit ain’t that serious. Haaaaaa
Yer friend 
Jake

I love the word ancient.  I ride the bike through the peninsula & stare off into where the hills meet the coast — the untouched rugged parts pounded by the waves & I can feel some kind of ancient spirit moving through my veins … there are times I’ve weeped & other times I just laugh … the mysteries & horrible truths, the victories & injustices … a sailboat silhouetted so serious & tragic — I remind myself there’s nothing “wrong” with me even though I don’t know if it’s true. You live your life in the alphabet after Z, looking for the outside of every side & search for the losers in every town to kick it with; the weirdos, the spirited all the other foul balls & the playbook used by the machine is obvious as a cockroach on a polished kitchen floor … there’s a price to pay for telling the truth & a steep wounded price to pay for turning the other cheek — for every brush stroke that’s an act of defiance against the assembly line, the obedient, an act of all out war against conformity & complacency … you paint and write in secret & if you’re lucky & skilled & true the muse is there for you every time … she takes over as I shift into fourth gear & disappear into the footsteps of my ancestors. 
It’s all hocus-pocus & voodoo & magic & I believe in all three because no one can tell me I can’t. And all the anxiety, backstabbers, fakes, depression, self doubt, negative self talk bring that shit on I’ll fight it every time. 
I feel better now. If you got this far — thank you. 
Your friend. 
Jake. 
“In the dark, on my own”
41 x 72”
All the way (((Live))) in the Port of Los Angeles.

I never know what’s going to happen when I walk to the studio, but somewhere in the back of my mind there’s always Ed Hardy & there’s always Gerhard Richter — the style is the varied style ,,, the freedom & all over the place in every direction brain put to canvas. I fight the urge to over paint; sometimes the quiet pastels the scratch of sandpaper the watered down paint, the photorealistic & the organic abstract … can be just enough … I listen to the crickets & smell the ocean air late into the night, erasing & erasing & sitting in my chair for hours … rain falls lightly on the metal roof, my wife tucked in with the heater on, petting a little bunny & I have to be as close to heaven as you can get … 
Hope everyone is having a nice Saturday night. 
Your friend,
Jake 
“No Direction Home”
41.5 x 66.5

It’s so embarrassing seeing people in real life that I don’t know, but “follow” on Instagram. I never know what to say. I scurry away. Avoid eye contact. And sweat through my sweatshirt wishing I just god damn stayed home. I always think of the Justin Townes Earle line: … “I rarely go out, and when I go 
I always hope I don't see anyone I know …” I suppose it’s ego. I just feel like an idiot most days, especially after “posting” this bullshit on Instagram. I click “post” & I can’t even look at the phone for several hours … I don’t know why it makes me itch so bad. I understand the positive parts of it & I don’t subscribe to anything negative in regards to this “app” … whatever. Been fun & challenging messing around with these last few paintings. The best part hiding away from the madness of the world for hours on end; continuing the tradition of all those who’ve made Art their lives throughout the centuries … the research & study is UNENDING. Thank you everyone for all the nice comments & to all those who continue to purchase work: I salute you!
Happy Sunday!
Jake 
“Talking To Myself”
31 x 67”
All the way (((Live))) in the beautiful Port of Los Angeles.

It’s true what they say, what I’ve heard all along: as you get older you have the ability to care less & less. I’m not talking about in a tough guy way or a nihilistic way; it’s difficult to describe … more like a bring it on & I’ll deal way. Whatever happens. Happens. I concentrate everyday on my own karmic debt & I focus on just plain old kindness. Harmlessness. Simplicity. Always push ups. Staying connected. There are days & days I don’t do jack shit but watch YouTube videos with Silvio. I’m on my phone as much as I feel like it & I do not feel guilty. I don’t leave the house for days & I could care less. Other days it’s yard work & repairs & insurance people & gas & oil changes — & bullshit after bullshit … I’ve been lied to, backstabbed, cheated & deceived — And cool guy’d. Boring. I’ve been threatened & had my ass whipped by regular people & the police. I’ve watched people die. I’ve walked past a crack house & a mansion. I’ve been uninvited & disappointed. I take it all in stride & roll that yoga mat out & thank my lucky stars I also know True Love & I know friendship. I know camaraderie. I know the joy of Art & the company of real Artists. The joy of my life. Tinkering around my shop hitting rewind on a song for the 20th time, splashing the paint around, trying to learn to tune a carburetor, pulling weeds … reading book after book before clicking the light out & sleeping like a baby. 
Whatever, FOREVER. 
Thank you always for the nice comments & the messages & everyone who supports the studio. I appreciate it with all my heart. 
Happy Friday night!
Your friend,
Jake 

“Don't tell me the moon is shining; show me the glint of light on broken glass”
72 x 108”
All the way (((Live in the LA HARBOR)))

I think people quit because they don’t get the reaction they’re looking for. I know it’s almost gotten to me. As time goes on I realize this is a young man’s game. Reactions. Acceptance. Applause. Accolades. In any creative pursuit you’ll get tested. Lord knows I have been. The one negative comment in 10 foot tall neon all over the ceiling as you try to sleep. Incessant self doubt. I’m not sure what the process or the time line is to get through this. You have to be lucky enough to be fully addicted & committed to something Artistic … to the books & the historical figures & the reference. You have to love with all your heart: the Source. The original version. That’s been the driving force behind my desire to work at this. Tapping in. Clocking the hours. Finding True Love in a mad mad world. As the song says: doin this shit without a record deal. All for the pure Love of it. It’s raining in Los Angeles & I do nothing but send auras of Love to all aggressors & I laugh at the negative voices as I learn how to heal … seeing myself clearly, not through the eyes of others, but through the eyes of my soul. Here it is. 
Happy Tuesday from the Coulter Jacobs Studio. All the way Live in the beautiful Port of Los Angeles. 

True Love
98 x 108”

The answer is: I don’t know. I don’t know when the next show is. It’s the same as the car hobby — the shows are secondary. The main priority is the day to day “cruising”. The hunting for parts & references. The process. The journey. I can’t even describe adequately how much I love it. The other part, the shows, the networking stuff, I just let it unfold organically. It’s a crazy thing to make Art & have people want to purchase it for their home or business. The shows & the galleries & openings & all that is super cool to me. I’m glad it’s secretive. I’m glad there’s kind of no rules. I don’t think I necessarily deserve anything & it bugs me when people complain. If it was easy everyone would just sit around all day painting pictures & have somebody else sell em for big money. In the back of my mind I guess my strategy has been to strive to make so much of it & have the work be so polished & individualistic it was undeniable. A lifelong project. This is my life. What I’ve dedicated my life to for over 20 years … To fit into every category & no category simultaneously. When I finish my daily yoga & mediate all I ask for, all I concentrate on is thanking God for bringing Art into my life; & I ask for help & guidance in being a sincere person. I can barely sleep most nights I’m so friggin jazzed to get into the studio & have that feeling where you know the Gods are zapping you with their energy. It’s real if you believe it. I guess you quit when the belief wanes. I make a conscious effort I practically beg that it never will leave me. The shows & the after parties all that stuff is wonderful, but it’s secondary. It’s not why I do this. There’s obviously a big negative lonely angry depressed void right in the middle of my heart & luckily this is how I fill it in …
So I don’t know when or where they will ever be displayed in public; when it’s meant to be, it’ll happen. 
Slow n steady wins the race. 
Lotsa Love from the Port of Los Angeles,
Your friend,
Jake 

“Man’s Ruin”
